# Cache System Design

Authors:  Daoxuan Xu, Jay Idema, Yifan Sun,

## Overview

GPUs are typically designed with a two-level cache.

Between the core and DRAM we might have an L1 cache and an L2 cache.

![diagram01.png](Cache_System_Design_Figs/diagram01.png)

The L1 cache offers caching of the Core.

It has very low latency but is also small in size.

And adding a second cache allows us to cache the DRAM - accessing the L2 cache is faster than accessing the DRAM itself.

So why not add more layers?

If you want to restrict latency to a certain number of cycles, you have to limit the number of layers.

And the flipside is true - if we increase the number of levels we increase the latency.

For a CPU it is common to have 3 levels of cache (or many more); however, there is a tradeoff between the number of cache layers AND the price for having each layer.

If you have a cache hit (where the data you want is stored in the top-most / first cache) then you have no issues.

However, when you have a cache miss, each additional cache layer adds to the latency of fetching the desired data.

By way of example - let's say each level of cache has a 10 cycle latency. If the data you're seeking is missing from two caches - that's 20 cycles of latency.

And if you have data missing from four layers of cache - that's 40 cycles of latency.

Thus - the more layers you have the more latency occurs for a cache miss.

So, increasing the number of layers might not be a good thing.

Especially for GPUs - caches are not as important as for CPUs.

So GPUs typically have fewer levels of caches.

## Cache lines

![diagram02.png](Cache_System_Design_Figs/diagram02.png)

When talking about caches, one of the first topics are cache lines.

The cache line is typically the smallest unit that can be fetched into a certain level.

In older-school GPUs it is typically 64 bytes in size.

And in newer GPUs it might be 128 bytes.

Lets say the core wants to read 4 bytes.

Then the L1 cache will send a cache line of 64 bytes of data.

Or, if there's a cache miss, the L2 cache will send 64 bytes of data.

And the L1 cache might reply with only 4 bytes of data to the core.

## Address Bus

![diagram03.png](Cache_System_Design_Figs/diagram03.png)

Between the core and the L1 cache, you have wires.
Typically there is an address bus - which is 64 bit - 64 wires.

However, it's actually shorter than 64 bits - some of the bits are always zero.

So it's actually more like using 48 bit addresses.

And you also have to track availability.

The core informs the L1 cache that it has a new message or a new request.

The L1 cache can also inform the core that it is available.

This lets the core know it can send a new message or request to the L1 cache.

Both of these availability signals are single bits that coordinate the core and the L1 cache.

## Data Bus

In addition to the address bus we also need a data bus.

![diagram04.png](Cache_System_Design_Figs/diagram04.png)

So the data bus is bi-directional.

For a read request, it's from the L1 to the core.

And for a write request, it's from the Core to L1.

How wide should it be?

It's typically set to 64 x 8; that is, 64 bytes.

Typically in hardware design we don't want to specify how many bytes we want to read.

Every time we read, we read a certain amount of bytes.

In this case, the cache line is the standard unit for reads and writes.

Every time we read a certain address:

- the address bus is set to a certain address
- the data bus will directly respond with the data.

For every layer of cache, typically 64 bytes is the smallest communication unit.

So when I read something, I always read 64 bytes - which is a cache line.

## Reading

![diagram05.png](Cache_System_Design_Figs/diagram05.png)

---

Let’s assume we have an L1 cache and we have the DRAM.

What's the read process?

If I send a request to the L1 cache, then I read the data.

It will check the appropriate 64 byte cache line.

The L1 cache will check if it's a hit or a miss.

If it's a hit, it replies with the data to the requestor.

![diagram06.png](Cache_System_Design_Figs/diagram06.png)

---

If it's a miss, it will go down to the DRAM.

The DRAM will always have the data - so it will respond with the data.

Once we respond with the data, it will

- Write the data into the appropriate cache line
- Reply with the data to the requestor

write the data into the appropriate L1 cache line.

This is the read process.

![diagram07.png](Cache_System_Design_Figs/diagram07.png)

So then the question is - what is actually stored in the cache line?

In the cache line there are typically a few things.

We typically need to have status.

This might be valid. Or invalid.

The cache line itself will always be there - but we want to check whether it is usable.

If it's not usable (invalid) then, even though there is data in the cache line, it's still a miss.

We also have something called a tag.

You can consider the tag as the address of this particular cache line.

When there is a request for the cache line, we have to compare the tag in the cache line with the tag in the request.

**When the cache line has an exact matching tag and the cache line is valid it is considered a cache hit.**

And for the rest of the cache line, we record the data. This is the real data.

Thus, for every cache line we have a status bit, tab bits, and data bits.

And that's the read process.

## Writing

![diagram08.png](Cache_System_Design_Figs/diagram08.png)

Now let's consider the write process.

It's much more complex - and so we have different policies.

If there's a write request that comes to the L1 cache, we can check if it's a hit or a miss.

If it's a write hit, we have two choices.

We can write the data to the cache line and update it.

But there's a problem with this design - **because for the corresponding address the cache line and DRAM are no longer in sync.**

![diagram09.png](Cache_System_Design_Figs/diagram09.png)

And so we would say the cache line is dirty - because it has newer information than what is in the DRAM.

For most cases, when there is only 1 core, it's not really a problem - because the next read will pull from the cache anyway.

However, if we mark the cache line as invalid (and so we're going to evict the data in the cache line) we need to write back to DRAM.

But this might create a problem - cache coherency.

![diagram09.png](Cache_System_Design_Figs/diagram09%201.png)

Say we have two cores and two L1 caches but one DRAM.

And let's say we wrote to the first L1 cache in a particular cache line - and it becomes dirty.

And then we want to read the same cache line from the other L1 cache and it's a miss - what should it do?

It will likely pull the data from DRAM.

Now the 2nd L1 cache has version 1 and the 1st L1 cache has version 2 of the data.

And this would wind up sending version 1 to the core.

Version 1 is the old data; ideally we want the version 2 data.

That's the cache coherency problem - we're reading old data - because the cache is no longer coherent.

And now, even if the first L1 cache writes to DRM, the L2 cache has the old data.

And if we keep reading the data - it will likely keep returning the old data.

Here is an example with multi-threaded code.

Here we are in a loop of some kind and want both threads to load and increment register $0.

| Thread #1 | Instruction | Thread #2 |
| --- | --- | --- |
| x | load $0, 0x1000 | x |
| x | add $0, $0, 1 | x |
| x | store 0x1000, $0 | x |

With cache incoherency, both threads would potentially be writing 1 - instead of the resulting impact being the correct value of 2.

Note: This is both a cache coherency problem and a memory consistency problem; these are related but different.

And if you write this sort of code without proper mutex or locking - this is called a race condition.

If we want to avoid this type of problem we could use a write-through cache policy.

# Write Through Caching Policy

Let's assume a two-level cache …

![diagram10.png](Cache_System_Design_Figs/diagram10.png)

When we have a write request and we have a cache hit, we will do two things at the same time.

We may write into the local (L1) cache.

And at the same time we may write into the L2 cache.

This guarantees the L2 cache always the same data as the L1 cache.

Most GPUs use a write-through cache.

The L1 cache in this scenario would be using a write-through caching policy and the L2 cache would be using a write-back caching policy.

![diagram11.png](Cache_System_Design_Figs/diagram11.png)

They can have different caching policies because a specific cache line can only exist in one memory location.

Remember that the bottom cache functions as memory-side cache.

So - one cache line may exist in both the L1 cache and the L2 cache.

But it will never exist in two L2 caches - because they are designed in an interleaving manner.

So 0x1000 might be in the first L2 cache and 0x1040 might be in the second L2 cache.
And 0x1080 might be in the first L2 cache and 0x10C0 might be the second L2 cache.

And so a particular cache line is always stored in a single L2 cache.

The L2 cache acts as a proxy for the DRAM.

So - any read will have to go through the L2 cache.

And if the L2 cache has newer data than the DRAM, it's totally okay.

Because every read will always go through the L2 cache.

And so it will always respond with the newer data.

GPUs solve the cache coherency problem by using a write-through cache policy and flushing the L1 cache between kernels.

The L2 cache might not need to be flushed but the L1 cache must be flushed.

## Write Allocation

How do we deal with a write where there is a cache miss?

![diagram12.png](Cache_System_Design_Figs/diagram12.png)

For a read, we can simply always read 64 bytes and only select the part we want to use.

If we only want to read 4 bytes, it doesn't hurt to read more; we just select the bytes that are useful.

For a write, we can write any number of bytes.

But we cannot always write a whole cache line.

If we only have 4 bytes of data - say we only have 1 integer - we can write 4 bytes of data.

So - there are two cases.

Let's assume we have a write miss with a full cache line.

We're writing a full line, that means we write 64 bytes - and it's a write miss.

What can we do?

We look for the cache line.

If it has valid data - we need to evict it and then fill in the cache line in the cache and mark it as dirty.

This process - the eviction and write of the new data - it's called Write Allocation.

And what if it's a write-through cache?

For every write into this L1 cache - we always write though - we always write to the L2 cache.

## Write Allocation with partial write

Given a caching policy using Write Allocation, the scenario of issuing a partial write with a cache miss is a special case.

We have to write something - but we're not writing a whole line.

Say we're only writing 4 bytes and it's a write miss.

If it was a Write Through cache policy without Write Allocation, we would simply write into the L2 cache - nothing special.

However, with Write Allocation, we have to interact with the L1 cache.

We have two options.

![diagram14.png](Cache_System_Design_Figs/diagram14.png)

Option 1:

Partial cache line with a **dirty mask**.

That is - for the cache line we mark it as invalid and keep the tag.
Then we mark as invalid all the data bits that aren't tied to what we're writing.
And we mark as dirty all the data bits that ARE tied to what we're writing.

![diagram15.png](Cache_System_Design_Figs/diagram15.png)

Option 2:

**Fetch then merge**

That is, rather than just sending the write request, we also send a read request.
When it comes back from L2, we merge the data we are writing with the actual data and then store it in the cache line.
In this case, we know it's valid.
We have all the data - and we don't need to have a dirty mask.

# Write Around Caching Policy

![diagram12.png](Cache_System_Design_Figs/diagram12%201.png)

We can also skip Write Allocation entirely if we have a cache miss.

This is because Write Allocation is optional.

When you have a write miss and you skip write allocation - that is what is known as a Write Around cache policy.

That means we're going around the L1 cache and writing directly to the L2 cache.

The Write Around caching policy is a Write Through caching policy without Write Allocation.

# Write Evict Caching Policy

There are two parts to this caching policy.

For both a cache miss and a cache hit - we always update the L2 cache.

This caching policy does not make use of write allocation.

Thus, if we have a cache hit - we invalidate the cache (evict).

|  | Write Through | Write Around | Write Evict | Write Back |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |

| Write - cache hit | Write local

## Write-Back Cache

In a writeback cache, when the processor writes new data to a memory location that is already cached, the cache line is updated within the cache but does not immediately write the new data back to main memory. The cache line is marked as "dirty" to indicate that it has been modified and stores the new data in the cache only. The modified data is written back to main memory only when the cache line is evicted or replaced by another cache line.

This delay in writing back modified data, called "writeback", is intended to reduce the number of writes to main memory, which can be a slow and resource-intensive operation. By delaying the “writeback” until a cache line is evicted or replaced, the writeback cache can take advantage of the fact that many memory locations are accessed frequently and may be modified several times before they are evicted from the cache.  However, a writeback cache can introduce memory synchronization issues when multiple processors or devices access the same memory location. This is because the cached data may be modified by one processor or device without immediately updating the data in main memory. As a result, if another processor or device accesses the same memory location, it may retrieve the outdated cached data instead of the most recent data stored in main memory.

[Messages sent to and received from the Top Port and Bottom Port of a WriteBack Cache]

![screaming.drawio.png](Cache_System_Design_Figs/screaming.drawio.png)

At a high level, the writeback cache in MGPUSIM handles read and write memory requests by receiving *mem.ReadReq* and *mem.WriteReq* objects to its *Top Port*. A *mem.ReadReq* is an implementation of the Akita Message interface, used to make a read request for data at *Address* with size *AccessByteSize*. A *mem.WriteReq* is also a Message, used to make a write request to write *Data* to memory starting at a given *Address*. 

The writeback cache maintain buffers for memory requests.  When a writeback cache has access to the data requested by a *mem.ReadReq*, it will send a *mem.DataReadyRsp*, which carries the data requested as well as the ID of the catalyst request, to its Top Port. Similarly, after fulfilling a write request, the cache will send a *mem.WriteDoneRsp*, which signifies a successful write, to its *Top Port*.

The writeback cache will handle the internal writeback policy and sends read and write requests to the memory module connected to its *Bottom Port*, which it, in turn, expects similar *mem.DataReadyRsp* and *mem.WriteDoneRsp* responses from.

## Internal Components:

The writeback cache for MGPUSIM is composed of individual, interacting components. At a high level, these components are: the Top Parser, the Directory, the Bank Stages, the MSHR Stage, and the Bottom Parser (WriteBuffer), as well as the Top Port and Bottom Port.

These components communicate directly with one another, by modifying the state of other components directly, or indirectly by passing Transaction objects between each other using buffers. Transactions are a monolithic class, which contain member variables for read requests, write requests, bank action requests, block and data information, and an ID.

### Top Parser

The *Top Parser* peeks at the *Top Port* every cycle and creates internal *Transaction* messages for the requests sent to the *Top Port*. These *transactions* are sent to the *Directory* stage, which will, in turn, process them.

### Directory

The *Directory* is the main management component for the writeback cache; it stores and manages block tag information and the current data present in the cache.

The directory stage is responsible for managing the cache's sets and blocks. The number of blocks and sets in the cache is determined by the cache's size and set associativity, which are determined by the cache *Builder*.

Set associativity determines how many blocks are stored in each set of the cache. For example, in a direct-mapped cache, each set contains only one block, while in a fully associative cache, all blocks are in a single set. In a n-way set-associative cache, each set contains n blocks.

The directory stage also handles block evictions from the cache. When a new block of data needs to be inserted into the cache but there are no empty blocks available in its set, an existing block is selected using the injected “VictimFinder” interface. The VictimFinder interface requires a single function FindVictim(set *Set) *Block, which returns the block in a set to be evicted, based on its policy.

Once the "VictimFinder" interface has identified the block to be evicted, the directory stage updates the cache directory to reflect the eviction by setting the new tag bits and locking the block until the new data arrives to be written.

The *Directory* performs operations based on *Transactions* sent from the *Top Parser*. Every tick, the *Directory* tries to process *numReqPerCycle* *Transactions*. If the address of the current request is currently marked for eviction, or locked, the request is temporarily ignored. Otherwise, the directory attempts to process the read or write request contained in the Transaction.

The Directory stage determines the set ID and block/cache line ID of a memory request with:

```go
cacheLineID = addr & (0xffffffffffffffff << blockSizeAsPowerOf2)  // Tag

setID = int(cacheLineID / uint64(d.BlockSize) % uint64(d.NumSets))// Index 
```

Then it checks the blocks of the set for the requested cache line as well as the MSHREntries of the MSHR Stage to determine if the request is a Miss, Hit, or MSHR Hit (see MSHR stage below).

If the request is a *mem.ReadReq*,

- If the data to be accessed gets an MSHR hit, the Directory sends a transaction to the MSHR stage to queue a *mem.DataReadyRsp* to send once the cache line arrives form the lower module. The Directory determines if the data has an MSHR hit by enumerating all the MSHR stage’s *MSHREntries*.
- If the read is a hit, a Transaction is sent to the Bank stages, which prompts them to send a *mem.DataReadyRsp* to the *Top Port* for the data requested.
- If the read is a miss, a cache line is evicted as described above based on the eviction policy. A transaction is sent to the MSHR stage to queue a *mem.DataReadyRsp* to send once the cache line arrives form the lower memory module. Transactions are also sent to the Bank Stages to send a read request to the lower memory module, and to finalize the eviction and write the data back to the lower memory module.

If the request is a *mem.WriteReq*,

- If the data to be written to gets an MSHR hit, the directory stage appends the transaction directly to the Requests array of the data’s active MSHR entry, without interacting with the MSHR stage. When the memory block is received from the lower memory module, data will be written to it based on this request by the MSHR stage and a *mem.WriteDoneRsp* will be sent to the Top Port.
- If a cache hit is achieved and the data block is not locked nor currently being read from, the directory stage ‘visits’ the block of the write (that is updates its status based on the eviction policy) and then sends a transaction for the write to the bank stage, which ultimately writes to the block and sends a *mem.WriteDoneRsp* to the *Top Port*.
- If a cache miss occurs, a cache line is evicted as described above based on the eviction policy, and a transaction to make the write is sent either to the bank stage if the write is for the entire line (no need to retrieve), or to the MSHR stage and the bank stages if only a portion of the cache line is being written to.

### Bank Stages

The *Bank Stages* finalize read and write requests for data which was already in the cache when the *Directory* processed the request. Upon receiving read and write request *transactions*, the *Bank Stages* either send a *mem.DataReadyRsp* to the *Top Port* with the requested data or writes the requested data to memory and sends a *mem.WriteDoneRsp* to the *Top Port* respectively.

Keyly, the Bank Stages handle evictions. When the Bank Stages receive transactions requesting the actions bankEvictAndFetch, bankEvictAndWrite, or bankEvict, the Bank Stages will read the memory from the evicted cache block and send a transaction with the evicted data to the WriteBuffer stage for finally sending to the lower memory module port as write request.

### MSHR Stage

MSHR (Miss Status Holding Register) is used in cache coherence protocols to track outstanding memory requests that have missed in a cache. MSHR entries can be resolved once the memory is retrieved from the lower memory module.

The *MSHR Stage* manages MSHREntries, which are created on misses by the *Directory*. The *MSHR stage* sends *mem.DataReadyRsp* messages to the *Top Port* when data is available in the cache for a read request and likewise sends *mem.WriteDoneRsp* messages to the *Top Port* when data for a write request is written. It is notable that the MSHR stage does NOT handle the actual writing on write misses once the data is fetched from the lower memory module; that is handled by the WriteBuffer stage, which, upon receiving a *mem.DataReadyRsp*, will remove MSHR entries for that data from the MSHR stage and send the Bank stages a transaction (action=bankWriteFetched) containing the fetched data.

### WriteBuffer/ParseBottom Stage

The *WriteBuffer* stage, also called the *ParseBottom* stage, sends *mem.ReadReq* and *mem.WriteReq* requests to a Bottom Port, which is found using the LowModuleFinder, detailed elsewhere. On evictions, the *Bank stages* send eviction transactions to the write buffer, prompting it to send a *mem.WriteReq* to the *Bottom Port*. On read misses, the *Directory* will send a transaction to the WriteBuffer, which will prompt it to send a *mem.ReadReq* to the *BottomPort*.

Inversely, the WriteBuffer reads from the cache’s *BottomPort* and processes *mem.DataReadyRsp* and *mem.WriteDoneRsp* responses; it sends transactions to the bank stages for writing data in the case of *mem.DataReadyRsp* messages.

## Low Module Finders

Low Module Finders build tables that map memory addresses (physical/virtual) to the component that can provide the data at the given address. They serve as generic lookup tables that take an address as input and return a port as the destination of the read/write requests.

Suppose we have a computing core that accesses data from several memory controllers that cover separated address ranges. The core needs to prepare read and write requests for the memory controllers. Akita requires the request sender to specify the destination of the requests (by setting the `dst` field of a request) so that the connection can deliver to the right destination. Therefore, we need to know the port that can serve the address to set the request destination. In this case, we need lookup tables (Low Module Finders) that contain the mapping between addresses and ports.

**Low Module Finder implementations.** We provide a few types of Low Module Finders, including `InterleavingLowModuleFinder`, `BankedLowModuleFinder`

`BnkedLowModuleFinder` contains two parameters: Banksize, and LowModules.  It usually serves for modules that will not search memory addresses for a loop(RDMA PMC).

`InterleavingLowModuleFinder` It usually serves for modules that will search memory addresses for a loop(L1 Cache and L2 Cache).

**L1 to L2 access use case.** A specific use case of Low Module Finder in MGPUSim is helping L1 caches to find the right L2 caches to access. 

In MGPUsim, different parts (L1, L2, RDMA) are connected together by `port`. L2 Cache serves data located in local memory address ranges for L1, and RDMA serves data located in other memory address ranges. Since the GPU L2 caches are memory-side caches implemented by a bank structure, the low module finder is built to hold all memory addresses of memory banks. Demonstrated in the figure below.

[Low Module Finder L1 to L2 access use case.drawio](Cache_System_Design_Figs/Low_Module_Finder_L1_to_L2_access_use_case.drawio)

[https://www.notion.so](https://www.notion.so)

Suppose 8 memory banks in L2 cache. Building a low module finder to hold the mapping relationship between memory addresses and the number of the memory bank. 

**Multi-GPU use case.** Low Module Finders are also essential for simulating multi-GPU systems. Since GPUs maintain their own memory, the memory of each GPU should use different physical address ranges. To run GPU kernels on multiple GPUs, developers need to distribute the data to all the GPUs. However, it is challenging to perfectly match the computing on a GPU with the data stored on the GPU. 

Suppose we want to run a matrix multiplication (C = A X B) kernel on a multi-GPU system. The host program may evenly distribute the matrices to the GPUs (as shown in the figure below). However, as we perform the multiplication operation, a GPU thread that calculates one block for matrix C may need to access whole columns of matrix A and whole rows of matrix B. As demonstrated in the figure below, the GPU will inevitably access data located on another GPU.

![gemm_corrected.drawio.svg](Cache_System_Design_Figs/gemm_corrected.drawio.svg)

To access data on another GPU, MGPUSim employs an RDMA engine, and the RDMA engine uses a Low Module Finder to specify which remote GPU contains the data. When the RDMA engine prepares remote access requests (read/write requests), the RDMA engine can use the Low module finder to identify the destination.

Suppose we build a 4 GPU system in MGPUSim, with each GPU having 4GB DRAM memory. We should divide the GPU system memory into several segments (as list the table below). The nature of the multi-GPU address arrangement determines that a `BankedLowModuleFinder` may be the best fit, with a bank size of 4GB.

| Address Range | Location |
| --- | --- |
| 0 GB - 4 GB | CPU |
| 4 GB - 8 GB | GPU 1 |
| 8 GB - 12 GB | GPU 2 |
| 12 GB - 16 GB | GPU 3 |
| 16 GB - 20 GB | GPU 4 |

Now we run a testbench on the wafer-scale GPU that we built, the data distributed on each GPM. If a GPM(sender) wants to find a data that does not at this GPM. The GPM(sender) will send a request to the RDMA module. Then, the RDMA will look up the table to find which GPM has such data. Then send a request to the RDMA module of that GPM(receiver). The data will be sent back from that GPM(receiver) to the GPM(sender). After the data is arrived, the GPM(sender) can continue to execute its own computation.

##
